ty among Turks Living in Germany -- tDiasporic Identity in Emine Sevgi Özdamar’s Mutterzunge -- tDifficult Stories: Generation, Genealogy, Gender in Zafer Șenocak’s Gefährliche Verwandtschaft and Monika Maron’s Pawels Briefe -- tDrowning or Waving: German Literature Today -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA collection of essays offering a nuanced understanding of the complex question of identity in today's Germany.This collection of fifteen essays by scholars from the UK, the US, Germany, and Scandinavia revisits the question of German identity. Unlike previous books on this topic, however, the focus is not exclusively on national identityin the aftermath of Hitler. Instead, the concentration is upon the plurality of ethnic, sexual, political, geographical, and cultural identities in modern Germany, and on their often fragmentary nature as the country struggles with the challenges of unification and international developments such as globalization, multiculturalism, and postmodernism. The multifaceted nature of German identity demands a variety of approaches: thus the essays are interdisciplinary, drawing upon historical, sociological, and literary sources. They are organized with reference to three distinct sections: Berlin, Political Formations, and Difference; yet at the same time they illuminate one another across the volume, offering a nuanced understanding of the complex question of identity in today's Germany. Topics include the new self-understanding of the Berlin Republic, Berlin as a public showcase, the Berlin architecture debate,the Walser-Bubis debate, fictions of German history and the end of the GDR, the impact of the German student movement on the FRG, Prime Minister Biedenkopf and the myth of Saxon identity, women in post-1989 Germany, trains as symbols and the function of the foreign in post-1989 fiction, identity construction among Turks in Germany and Turkish self-representation in post-1989 fiction, the state of German literature today. Contributors: Frank Brunssen, Ulrike Zitzlsperger, Janet Stewart, Kathrin Schödel, Karen Leeder, Ingo Cornils, Peter Thompson, Chris Szejnmann, Sabine Lang, Simon Ward, Roswitha Skare, Eva Kolinsky, Margaret Littler, Katharina Gerstenberger, and Stuart Parkes. Stuart Taberner is Lecturer in German, and Frank Finlay is Professor of German and Head of the Department of German, both at the University of Leeds, UK.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xPsychological aspects. 0aNational characteristics, German. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aBerlin Architecture.  aBerlin Republic.  aCultural Identity.  aEthnic Identity.  aGerman History.  aGerman Identity.  aGerman Literature.  aGerman Student Movement.  aNational Identity.  aPolitical Identity.  aTurkish Self-representation.1 aBrunssen, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornils, Ingo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinlay, Frank, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGerstenberger, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKolinsky, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeeder, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittler, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParkes, Keith Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParkes, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc